    <item>
      <title>closure</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/closure/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/closure/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;closure&lt;/strong&gt; is a &lt;a href=&#34;first-class-function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;first-class function&lt;/a&gt; bundled together with a reference to the environment in which it was defined. When the function is later called — possibly far from where it was created — it can still access the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/variable.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;variables&lt;/a&gt; that were in scope at the time of its creation.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Consider a function &lt;code&gt;makeAdder(n)&lt;/code&gt; that returns a new function adding &lt;code&gt;n&lt;/code&gt; to its argument. After &lt;code&gt;addThree = makeAdder(3)&lt;/code&gt;, calling &lt;code&gt;addThree(10)&lt;/code&gt; returns &lt;code&gt;13&lt;/code&gt;. The returned function is a closure: it &amp;ldquo;closes over&amp;rdquo; the variable &lt;code&gt;n&lt;/code&gt;, capturing the value &lt;code&gt;3&lt;/code&gt; even though &lt;code&gt;makeAdder&lt;/code&gt; has already returned and its local scope has, in principle, ended.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>composition</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/composition/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/composition/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Composition&lt;/strong&gt; is the operation of combining two &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;functions&lt;/a&gt; so that the output of the first becomes the input of the second. Given a function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;f : A \to B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and a function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;g : B \to C&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, their composition &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;g \circ f&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is a new function from &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; to &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;C&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that applies &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;f&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; first, then &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;g&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; to the result:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34; display=&#34;block&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;(g \circ f)(x) = g(f(x))&#xD;&#xA;&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;Composition is the primary mechanism by which &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/functional/index.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;functional programming&lt;/a&gt; builds complex behavior from simple parts. Rather than writing a single large function, a functional programmer writes small &lt;a href=&#34;pure-function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;pure functions&lt;/a&gt; and wires them together through composition.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>currying</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/currying/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/currying/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Currying&lt;/strong&gt; is the transformation of a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;function&lt;/a&gt; that takes multiple arguments into a sequence of functions, each taking a single argument. A function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;f(a, b, c)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; becomes a function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;f(a)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that returns a function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;g(b)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that returns a function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;h(c)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that produces the result. In notation:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34; display=&#34;block&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;×&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;×&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;D&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mspace width=&#34;1em&#34;/&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⟶&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mspace width=&#34;1em&#34;/&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34; lspace=&#34;0em&#34; rspace=&#34;0em&#34;&gt;′&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;D&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;f : A \times B \times C \to D \quad\longrightarrow\quad f&amp;#x27; : A \to (B \to (C \to D))&#xD;&#xA;&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;The concept is named after Haskell Curry, though it was first described by Moses Schönfinkel. In the lambda calculus, all functions naturally take a single argument — multi-argument functions are always expressed as curried chains of single-argument abstractions. The expression &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;.&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;.&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda x.\, \lambda y.\, x + y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; takes &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and returns a function that takes &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and returns &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x + y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>first-class function</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/first-class-function/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/first-class-function/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;first-class function&lt;/strong&gt; is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;function&lt;/a&gt; that a language treats as a value: it can be stored in a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/variable.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;variable&lt;/a&gt;, passed as an argument to another function, and returned as a result from a function. The function itself — not its name or its result — is the value that moves through the program.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This property is what makes &lt;a href=&#34;higher-order-function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;higher-order functions&lt;/a&gt; possible. If functions are not first-class, then &lt;code&gt;map&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;filter&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;reduce&lt;/code&gt; cannot exist in their general form, because there is no way to hand a function to another function as an argument.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>higher-order function</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/higher-order-function/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/higher-order-function/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;higher-order function&lt;/strong&gt; is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;function&lt;/a&gt; that either takes one or more functions as arguments, returns a function as its result, or both. The concept is central to &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/functional/index.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;functional programming&lt;/a&gt;, where functions are treated as values that can be passed around like numbers or strings.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The most common higher-order functions are &lt;strong&gt;map&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;filter&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;reduce&lt;/strong&gt; (sometimes called &lt;strong&gt;fold&lt;/strong&gt;). Each takes a function and a collection as inputs and applies the function across the collection in a different way:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>immutability</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/immutability/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/immutability/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Immutability&lt;/strong&gt; is the &lt;a href=&#34;../../../../../../../sociology/terms/property.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;property&lt;/a&gt; of data that cannot be modified after it is created. An immutable value is fixed at the moment of its creation; any operation that appears to &amp;ldquo;change&amp;rdquo; it instead produces a new value, leaving the original intact.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In contrast, mutable data can be altered in place. A mutable list allows elements to be added, removed, or replaced directly. An immutable list does not — appending an element produces a new list that contains all the original elements plus the new one, while the original list remains unchanged.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>pure function</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/pure-function/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/pure-function/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;pure function&lt;/strong&gt; is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;function&lt;/a&gt; that satisfies two conditions: it always produces the same output when given the same inputs, and it causes no observable changes outside itself (no side effects).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The first condition is called &lt;strong&gt;referential transparency&lt;/strong&gt;. If a function &lt;code&gt;add(2, 3)&lt;/code&gt; returns &lt;code&gt;5&lt;/code&gt;, it returns &lt;code&gt;5&lt;/code&gt; every time, regardless of when or where the call happens. The function does not consult a database, read the current time, or depend on any state that might change between calls. Its output is determined entirely by its inputs.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>recursion</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/recursion/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/tech/domains/computing/domains/software/domains/programming/domains/functional/terms/recursion/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recursion&lt;/strong&gt; is a technique in which a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/technology/disciplines/computing/software/programming/terms/function.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;function&lt;/a&gt; solves a problem by calling itself with a simpler version of the same problem. Each recursive call reduces the problem until it reaches a &lt;strong&gt;base case&lt;/strong&gt; — a version simple enough to solve directly without further recursion.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A classic example is computing the factorial of a number. The factorial of 5 (written 5!) is 5 times 4 times 3 times 2 times 1. A recursive definition captures this: the factorial of n is n multiplied by the factorial of (n - 1), and the factorial of 1 is 1. The function calls itself repeatedly, each time with a smaller number, until it reaches 1 and begins returning results back up the chain of calls.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
